My pre-nam experiences <br><br>
I grew up in a cardboard shack at the city dump in Casa Grande, Arizona, my father had lost our large farm in New Mexico because we had been taxed differently then others who were not Hispanic. Two years later when I was four years old, my father was killed in an auto accident where a drunk drive ran him off the road. My mother raised the thirteen of us on her own. As a young teenager one day I saw my brother dressed up in his green Army reserve uniform and admired him for it. I wished then that when I grew up that there would be a war going on so that I could go. <br><br>
In high school, I fell in love with my English teacher who had nice long legs, but I canĺt remember her name today. I remember my art teacher, Karen Kuykendale because she encouraged me to utilize my poetic writing and drawing abilities.   She gave me a book, I still have that opened my mind to the world of writing, expressions, and life.<br><br>
I spent the summer of 1965 in Fresno, California with my sister. It was there that I met an older girl who had just graduated from High School. I quit school the following spring and went to live with my sister to help her because she was dying of cancer.<br><br>
The girl I had met the summer before and I started to see each other and she soon wanted to get married and while I didnĺt love her nor had we been together she threaten to commit suicide if I didnĺt marry her. Most of her friends were by then married and a few weeks before she had broken up with her boyfriend. When she swallowed a whole bottle of aspirins, I feared she was serious and agreed to marry her.<br><br>
We were married that summer and that day she asked how long did I think the marriage would last. I remember quoting to her from the book my teacher had given me, <br>
&quot;For our age and economy bracket, we have a 47.3% chance of staying together for...,&quot; I added , &quot;Two-weeks.&quot; <br><br>
We lasted less then that, we tried on and off again until I turned 18 and joined the Marine Corps to get away from her that date.  ON New years eve 1966 I arrived at the Marine Corps Recruiting Depot in San Diego, California. She was out with her former boy friend that night. <br><br>
I knew that I would be going to war and I wanted the best training possible and to me the Corps would provide it and thatĺs why I joined the Marine Corps.<br><br>
There, I learned to value and to take life. To truly believed in American, in our patriotic duty, in courage, commitment and honor.  In Nam I saw the agony the Vietnamese were suffering and truly wanted to help them win the war. I learned survival meant more then winning the next battle, that friendship, trust and commitment to each other and to our country was what helped many of us have hope for returning home.<br><br>
Those are my thoughts and I am, <br>
Cook Barela <br>

